    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'During the reign of King Herod the Great of Judea, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        there was a Jewish priest named Zechariah  who served in the temple as part
        of the priestly order of Abijah.  His wife, Elizabeth, was also from a family
        of priests, and was a descendant of Aaron. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  Herod the Great ruled in Israel under the Emperor of Rome, the
          first of a succession of Herodian \u201Ckings.\u201D      Zechariah means
          \u201CGod has remembered.\u201D Elizabeth means \u201Coath\u201D or \u201Ccovenant
          of God.\u201D The gospel of Luke opens and closes with the story of a priest.
          It begins with Zechariah, the fallible human priest after the order of
          Aaron, and ends with our perfect High Priest after the order of Melchizedek,
          Jesus Christ.      King David organized the priests into twenty-four divisions,
          and Abijah was the head of one of the priestly families. See  ,  ;  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'They were both righteous before God, living virtuously and following
        the commandments of the Lord blamelessly. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: But they were childless since Elizabeth was barren, and now they both
        were quite old.
      comments: []
    - name: '8-9: '
      title: 
      number: 8-9
      content: "One day, Zechariah\u2019s priestly order was on duty and he was serving
        as priest. He was chosen by the casting of lots (according to the custom
        of the priesthood) so the honor fell upon Zechariah to enter the Holy Place
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and burn incense before the Lord. "
      comments:
      - number: "1:8\u20139"
        content: "  Some have said there were twenty thousand priests in Christ\u2019s
          time, so that no priest would ever offer incense more than once. This was
          a once-in-a-lifetime moment for Zechariah. The burning of incense before
          the Lord was done twice daily, once in the morning and once in the afternoon
          ().    "
    - name: '8-9: '
      title: 
      number: 8-9
      content: "One day, Zechariah\u2019s priestly order was on duty and he was serving
        as priest. He was chosen by the casting of lots (according to the custom
        of the priesthood) so the honor fell upon Zechariah to enter the Holy Place
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and burn incense before the Lord. "
      comments:
      - number: "1:8\u20139"
        content: "  Some have said there were twenty thousand priests in Christ\u2019s
          time, so that no priest would ever offer incense more than once. This was
          a once-in-a-lifetime moment for Zechariah. The burning of incense before
          the Lord was done twice daily, once in the morning and once in the afternoon
          ().    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'A large crowd of worshipers had gathered to pray outside the temple
        at the hour when incense was being offered. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: All at once an angel of the Lord appeared to him, standing just to
        the right of the altar of incense. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: '  The angel appeared on the south side of the Holy Place, between
          the altar of incense and the golden lampstand.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Zechariah was startled and overwhelmed with fear. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "But the angel reassured him, saying, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Zechariah! God is showing grace to you. For I have come to
        tell you that your prayer  for a child has been answered. Your wife, Elizabeth,
        will bear you a son and you are to name him John. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:13
        content: "  Luke uses this phrase, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,\u201D seven
          times in his gospel (,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ).      The Greek verb allows for a
          possible translation of \u201Cprayer you don\u2019t even pray anymore.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'His birth will bring you much joy and gladness. [[COMMENT(0)]] Many
        will rejoice because of him, '
      comments:
      - number: 1:14
        content: "  Luke is the gospel of joy! There are nine reasons for joy in
          this book: (1) The joy of Christ\u2019s life,  . (2) The greatness of Jesus, 
          . (3) The joy of heaven over the birth of Christ,  . (4) The joy of God\u2019s
          Word in our hearts,  . (5) The joys of a ministry of power and our names
          written in heaven,  ,  . (6) The heavenly joys of salvation,  ,  . (7)
          The joys of condescending love,  . (8) The joys of overwhelming mysteries, 
          . (9) The resurrection and the blessings that are ours in Christ,  .    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "and he will be one of the great ones in the sight of God. He will
        drink no wine or strong drink, [[COMMENT(0)]] but he will be filled with
        the Holy Spirit even while still in his mother\u2019s womb. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:15
        content: '  Most likely, John was to be a Nazarite from birth, one totally
          set apart for God and who would fulfill the Nazarite vow found in  .    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'And he will persuade many in Israel to convert and turn back to the
        Lord their God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He will go before the Lord as a forerunner, with the same power and
        anointing [[COMMENT(0)]] as Elijah the prophet. He will be instrumental in
        turning the hearts of the fathers in tenderness back to their children and
        the hearts of the disobedient back to the wisdom of their righteous fathers.
        And he will prepare a united people   who are ready for the Lord\u2019s appearing.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cspirit.\u201D      The words \u201Cunited people\u201D
          are found in the Aramaic text.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Zechariah asked the angel, \u201CHow do you expect me to believe
        this? I\u2019m an old man and my wife is too old to give me a child. What
        sign can you give me to prove this will happen?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then the angel said, \u201CI am Gabriel. [[COMMENT(0)]] I stand beside
        God himself. He has sent me to announce to you this good news. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:19
        content: "  The name Gabriel means \u201CGod\u2019s hero\u201D or \u201CGod\u2019s
          mighty one.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "But now, since you did not believe my words, you will be stricken
        silent and unable to speak [[COMMENT(0)]] until the day my words have been
        fulfilled at their appointed time and a child is born to you. That will be
        your sign!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:20
        content: '  Since Zechariah asked for a sign rather than believe the word
          of the Lord, he was given the sign of silence. Unbelief keeps a priest
          from speaking until faith arises.      This is the first spoken message
          from heaven in more than four hundred years. The last person before Zechariah
          to receive a message given by angels was also named Zechariah. See  .    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Meanwhile, the crowds outside kept expecting him to come out. They
        were amazed over Zechariah\u2019s delay, [[COMMENT(0)]] wondering what could
        have happened inside the sanctuary. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: '  They were waiting outside for the priest to come out and speak
          over them the customary Aaronic blessing found in  .    '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "When he finally did come out, he tried to talk, but he couldn\u2019t
        speak a word, and they realized from his gestures that he had seen a vision
        while in the Holy Place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'He remained mute as he finished his days of priestly ministry in
        the temple and then went back to his own home. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Soon afterward his wife, Elizabeth, became pregnant and went into
        seclusion for the next five months. '
      comments: []
    - name: "25: Angelic Prophecy of Jesus\u2019 Birth"
      title: "Angelic Prophecy of Jesus\u2019 Birth"
      number: 25
      content: "With joy she exclaimed, \u201CSee how kind it is of God to gaze upon
        me [[COMMENT(0)]] and take away the disgrace of my barrenness!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:25
        content: '  This phrase is translated from the Aramaic text.    '
    - name: '26-27: '
      title: 
      number: 26-27
      content: "During the sixth month of Elizabeth\u2019s pregnancy, the angel Gabriel
        was sent from God\u2019s presence to an unmarried girl [[COMMENT(0)]] named
        Mary, living in Nazareth, a village in Galilee.  She was engaged  to a man
        named Joseph, a true descendant of King David. "
      comments:
      - number: "1:26\u201327"
        content: "  Many translations have the word  . It is a possible translation
          of the Greek word  , but its most common usage implies \u201Ca girl of
          marriageable age.\u201D It is made explicit in    and    that Mary was
          indeed a virgin.      The Aramaic word translated \u201CGalilee\u201D here
          means \u201Crevealed.\u201D It is only fitting that God would first be
          \u201Crevealed\u201D in a village in Galilee. Nazareth means \u201Cbranch.\u201D
          Jesus grew up as the \u201CBranch\u201D of the Lord in the city of the
          \u201Cbranch.\u201D      This betrothal period usually lasted one year,
          and unfaithfulness on the part of the bride during the engagement would
          have been punishable by death.    "
    - name: '26-27: '
      title: 
      number: 26-27
      content: "During the sixth month of Elizabeth\u2019s pregnancy, the angel Gabriel
        was sent from God\u2019s presence to an unmarried girl [[COMMENT(0)]] named
        Mary, living in Nazareth, a village in Galilee.  She was engaged  to a man
        named Joseph, a true descendant of King David. "
