    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'That night, in a field [[COMMENT(0)]] near Bethlehem, shepherds were
        watching over their flocks. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:8
        content: '  Many scholars believe that these could be the same fields where
          sacrificial flocks were kept for temple worship. How fitting that these
          shepherds would hear the announcement of the birth of the Lamb of God.
          Others believe these fields could have been near the field of Boaz, or
          the fields where David once watched over the flocks of his father, Jesse.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Suddenly, an angel of the Lord appeared in radiant splendor before
        them, lighting up the field with the blazing glory of God, and the shepherds
        were terrified! '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But the angel reassured them, saying, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,
        for I have come to bring you good news, the most joyous news the world has
        ever heard! And it is for everyone everywhere! "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'For today in Bethlehem [[COMMENT(0)]] a rescuer was born for you.
        He is the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the Messiah.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: "  The Greek text says, \u201Cthe city of David.\u201D      Translated
          literally from the Aramaic text. This is one of the most amazing statements
          found in the Gospels declaring the deity of Jesus Christ.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "You will recognize him by this miraculous sign: You will find a baby
        wrapped in strips of cloth and lying in the feeding trough!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:12
        content: "  A baby lying in a feeding trough where animals were kept nearby,
          wrapped in strips of cloths, became a sign of the Man-Savior\u2019s life
          on earth. He entered the world as a lowly baby, and though he is the mighty
          God, he lived his life on earth in gentleness before all. The shepherds
          that night were possibly near Bethlehem at Migdal Eder, \u201Cthe [watch]
          tower of the flock.\u201D This would fulfill both the prophecies of   
          and  , which say, \u201Cto you it [he] will come, your dominion [kingdom]
          from old will arrive.\u201D It was at the lower floor of the watchtower
          (Migdal Eder) that the birthing of the Passover lambs would take place.
          Selected ewes that were about to give birth would be brought there. After
          the birth of the lambs, the priestly shepherds would wrap the lambs in
          cloth and lay them in a manger lined with soft hay to prevent them from
          hurting themselves, for Passover lambs must be unblemished with no bruise
          or broken bone. The miracle sign for these priestly shepherds would be
          a baby boy lying where the Passover lamb should be\u2014in a manger, wrapped
          in strips of cloth. It was at the cradle of Jesus Christ that the kingdom
          from ancient times arrived on earth.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then all at once in the night sky, a vast number of glorious angels
        appeared, the very armies of heaven! And they all praised God, singing:'
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CGlory to God in the highest realms of heaven!For there is peace
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and a good hope  given to the sons of men.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: "  Luke\u2019s Gospel is the Gospel of peace. The four prominent
          sacrifices of the Old Testament are emphasized in the four Gospels. In
          Matthew we see the death of Christ in the figure of the trespass offering,
          in Mark the sin offering, in Luke the peace offering, and in John the burnt
          offering. The peace God gives us is emphasized in Luke\u2019s Gospel, which
          is why the angels announced peace and hope. On the day of his resurrection
          Jesus said, \u201CPeace to you.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic.
          The Greek is \u201Cgood will among people\u201D or \u201Cgood will among
          people with whom he is pleased.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When the choir of angels disappeared and returned to heaven, the
        shepherds said to one another, \u201CLet\u2019s go! Let\u2019s hurry and
        find this Word [[COMMENT(0)]] who is born in Bethlehem and see for ourselves
        what the Lord has revealed to us.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: '  The Greek is the word  .    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: So they hurried off and found their way to Mary and Joseph. And there
        was the baby, lying in a feeding trough.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Upon seeing this miraculous sign, the shepherds recounted what had
        just happened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Everyone who heard the shepherds\u2019 story was astonished by what
        they were told."
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: But Mary treasured all these things in her heart and often pondered
        what they meant.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: Baby Jesus Dedicated in the Temple'
      title: Baby Jesus Dedicated in the Temple
      number: 20
      content: The shepherds returned to their flock, ecstatic over what had happened.
        They praised God and glorified him for all they had heard and seen for themselves,
        just like the angel had said.
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "On the day of the baby\u2019s circumcision ceremony, eight days after
        his birth, his parents gave him the name Jesus, the name prophesied by the
        angel before he was born. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Forty days after the birth of her son, Mary\u2019s time of purification
        had completed, so she came to the temple with a sacrifice, according to the
        law of Moses. [[COMMENT(0)]] So Mary and Joseph took baby Jesus to Jerusalem
        to be dedicated before the Lord.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:22
        content: "  This comes from  . When a son was born, the mother went through
          a forty-day period of purification, and then she was to offer a sacrifice
          to complete the process.      The ark of the covenant, signifying the presence
          of God, had been absent from the temple since 586 BC, when the Babylonians
          destroyed the temple. Herod\u2019s temple had no ark of covenant until
          Jesus came into the temple that day. God returned to the temple when Mary
          carried her baby into its courts. What a dramatic moment! See  .    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "For it is stated in the law of the Lord, \u201CEvery firstborn male
        shall be set apart for God\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:23
        content: '  ,  .    '
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "and is required to offer a prescribed sacrifice, \u201Ceither a pair
        of turtledoves or two young pigeons.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:24
        content: '  Because Joseph and Mary were rather poor, not yet having received
          the gifts brought by the wise men, they offered a pair of doves or pigeons
          instead of a lamb (). Mary offered a sin offering, showing her need of
          a Savior. Jesus would one day be offered as her true Lamb.    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "As they came to the temple to fulfill this requirement, an elderly
        man was there waiting\u2014a resident of Jerusalem whose name was Simeon.
        He was a very good man, a lover of God who kept himself pure, and the Spirit
        of holiness rested upon him. Simeon believed in the imminent appearing of
        the one called \u201CThe Refreshing of Israel.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:25
        content: "  \u201CThe Refreshing of Israel\u201D is a name for Jesus that
          can also be translated \u201CThe Encourager of Israel.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'For the Holy Spirit had revealed to him [[COMMENT(0)]] that he would
        not see death before he saw the Messiah, the Anointed One of God. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:26
        content: "  Simeon\u2019s name means \u201Che who hears.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Keeping his promise, the Holy Spirit led Simeon to be in the temple
        court at the very moment Jesus\u2019 parents entered to fulfill the requirement
        of the sacrifice."
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Simeon cradled the baby in his arms and praised God and prophesied:'
      comments: []
    - name: '29-31: '
      title: 
      number: 29-31
      content: "\u201CLord and Master, I am your loving servant,and now I can die
        content,for you have fulfilled your promise to me.With my own eyes I have
        seen your Word, [[COMMENT(0)]]the Savior you sent into the world."
      comments:
      - number: "2:29\u201331"
        content: "  Or \u201CManifestation\u201D in the Aramaic.    "
    - name: '29-31: '
      title: 
      number: 29-31
      content: "\u201CLord and Master, I am your loving servant,and now I can die
        content,for you have fulfilled your promise to me.With my own eyes I have
        seen your Word, [[COMMENT(0)]]the Savior you sent into the world."
      comments:
      - number: "2:29\u201331"
        content: "  Or \u201CManifestation\u201D in the Aramaic.    "
    - name: '29-31: '
      title: 
      number: 29-31
      content: "\u201CLord and Master, I am your loving servant,and now I can die
        content,for you have fulfilled your promise to me.With my own eyes I have
        seen your Word, [[COMMENT(0)]]the Savior you sent into the world."
      comments:
      - number: "2:29\u201331"
        content: "  Or \u201CManifestation\u201D in the Aramaic.    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "He will be glory for your people Israel,and the Revelation-Light
        for all people everywhere!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:32
        content: '  This is a fulfillment of many Old Testament prophecies, such
          as those found in  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Mary and Joseph stood there, awestruck over what was being said about
        their baby.Simeon then blessed them and prophesied over Mary, saying:'
      comments: []
    - name: '34-35: '
      title: 
      number: 34-35
      content: "\u201CA painful sword [[COMMENT(0)]] will one day pierce your inner
        being,for your child will be rejected by many in Israel.And the destiny of
        your child is this:he will be laid down  as a miracle signfor the downfall 
        and resurrection of many in Israel.Many will oppose this sign, but it will
        expose to allthe innermost thoughts of their hearts before God.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "2:34\u201335"
        content: "  This is a unique Greek word used for \u201Csword.\u201D Literally
          it means \u201Ca large broadsword.\u201D      The Greek word translated
          \u201Cappointed\u201D actually means \u201Cto lie down.\u201D Jesus was
          laid down on a cross and in a tomb for us and rose again for us.      The
          Greek word translated \u201Cfalling\u201D can also be translated \u201Cdownfall\u201D
          or \u201Cdestruction.\u201D Perhaps this was a prophecy of the cross of
          Jesus Christ, where many will rise or fall depending on what they do with
          Jesus\u2019 death and resurrection. We are all destined to be joined to
          him in his death and resurrection (). Every believer experiences both a
          \u201Cdownfall\u201D and a \u201Cresurrection.\u201D    "
