    - name: '18-19: '
      title: 
      number: 18-19
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CThe Spirit of the Lord is upon me, and he has anointed
        me to be hope</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>for the poor, healing for the
        brokenhearted, and new eyes</JESUS>    <JESUS>for the blind, and to preach
        to prisoners,</JESUS>    <JESUS>\u2018You are set free!\u2019 I have come
        to share</JESUS>  <JESUS>the message of Jubilee,</JESUS>    <JESUS>for the
        time of God\u2019s great acceptance</JESUS>    <JESUS>has begun.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "4:18\u201319"
        content: "  Or \u201Cgood news.\u201D      The Greek word is translated \u201Cgazed
          into heaven\u201D in  .      Literally \u201Cprisoners of war.\u201D     
          See  ;  ;  . The Isaiah passage is associated with the proclamation of
          the Year of Jubilee. The Greek word used here implies a cycle of time.
          Jesus clearly defined his mission by reading these words of the prophet
          Isaiah.      Or \u201Cfavor.\u201D This phrase can be translated \u201Cthe
          years when God will accept man.\u201D      This is quoted from  . Jesus
          spoke this bold decree over his life and identity before he worked miracles.    "
    - name: '18-19: '
      title: 
      number: 18-19
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CThe Spirit of the Lord is upon me, and he has anointed
        me to be hope</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>for the poor, healing for the
        brokenhearted, and new eyes</JESUS>    <JESUS>for the blind, and to preach
        to prisoners,</JESUS>    <JESUS>\u2018You are set free!\u2019 I have come
        to share</JESUS>  <JESUS>the message of Jubilee,</JESUS>    <JESUS>for the
        time of God\u2019s great acceptance</JESUS>    <JESUS>has begun.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "4:18\u201319"
        content: "  Or \u201Cgood news.\u201D      The Greek word is translated \u201Cgazed
          into heaven\u201D in  .      Literally \u201Cprisoners of war.\u201D     
          See  ;  ;  . The Isaiah passage is associated with the proclamation of
          the Year of Jubilee. The Greek word used here implies a cycle of time.
          Jesus clearly defined his mission by reading these words of the prophet
          Isaiah.      Or \u201Cfavor.\u201D This phrase can be translated \u201Cthe
          years when God will accept man.\u201D      This is quoted from  . Jesus
          spoke this bold decree over his life and identity before he worked miracles.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'After he read this he rolled up the scroll, handed it back to the
        attendant, and sat down. Everyone stared at Jesus, wondering what he was
        about to say. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then he added, <JESUS>\u201CToday, these Scriptures came true in
        front of you.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Everyone was impressed by how well Jesus spoke, in awe of the beautiful
        words of grace that came from his lips. But they said among themselves, \u201CWho
        does he think he is?  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.</smallcaps> Isn\u2019t he
        Joseph\u2019s son, who grew up here in Nazareth?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:22
        content: '  This is the inferred meaning of their criticism of Jesus. His
          true Father was not Joseph, but      '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Jesus said to them, <JESUS>\u201CI suppose you\u2019ll quote me the
        proverb, \u2018Doctor, go and heal yourself before you try to heal others.\u2019
        And you\u2019ll say, \u2018Work the miracles here in your hometown that we
        heard you did in Capernaum.\u2019</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: <JESUS>But let me tell you, no prophet is welcomed or honored in his
        own hometown.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CIsn\u2019t it true that many widows lived in the land
        of Israel during the days of the prophet Elijah when he locked up the heavens
        for three and a half years and brought a devastating famine over all the
        land?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "<JESUS>But he wasn\u2019t sent to any of the widows living in that
        region. Instead, he was sent to a foreign place, to a widow in Zarephath
        of Sidon.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:26
        content: "  Zarephath means \u201Cthe place of refining.\u201D Sidon means
          \u201Cfishery\u201D and was a Phoenician seaport city.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "<JESUS>Or have you not considered that the prophet Elisha healed
        only Naaman,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>the Syrian, rather than one
        of the many Jewish lepers living in the land?\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:27
        content: "  Both the Aramaic and Greek texts have \u201CNaaman the Aramean\u201D
          or \u201Cdescendant of Aram.\u201D The Arameans inhabited what is now Syria.
          Naaman means \u201Cpleasantness.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "When everyone present heard Jesus\u2019 words, they erupted with
        furious rage. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:28
        content: "  Jesus\u2019 listeners got the point of his sermon. His statements
          implied that he would take his miracle ministry to non-Jewish people. Jubilee
          had come, not only for them, but for those they hated. This infuriated
          them enough to want to kill Jesus.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'They mobbed Jesus and threw him out of the city, dragging him to
        the edge of the cliff on the hill on which the city had been built, ready
        to hurl him off. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: Jesus Confronts a Demonized Man'
      title: Jesus Confronts a Demonized Man
      number: 30
      content: But he walked right through the crowd, leaving them all stunned. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 4:30
        content: "  The Greek text clearly implies it was a supernatural event. After
          hearing Jesus\u2019 first sermon, they wanted to throw him off a cliff!    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Jesus went to Capernaum [[COMMENT(0)]] in Galilee and taught the
        people on the Sabbath day. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:31
        content: "  Capernaum means \u201Cthe village of Nahum\u201D and Nahum means
          \u201Ccomforted.\u201D Jesus did many miracles and made his Galilean base
          of ministry in \u201Cthe village of the comforted.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: His teaching stunned and dazed [[COMMENT(0)]] them, for he spoke with
        penetrating words and great authority.
      comments:
      - number: 4:32
        content: "  The Greek word used here,  , is a strong verb that means \u201Cstruck
          with amazement,\u201D \u201Castonished,\u201D \u201Cpanic stricken,\u201D
          \u201Cshocked\u201D or \u201Csomething that takes your breath away\u201D
          (like being hit with a blow), or \u201Cto expel,\u201D \u201Cto drive out.\u201D
          Jesus spoke with such glory and power emanating from him that his words
          were like thunderbolts into their hearts. May we hear his words today in
          the same way.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'In the congregation, there was a demonized man, who screamed out
        with a loud voice, '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CGo away and leave us alone. We know who you are. You\u2019re
        Jesus of Nazareth, God\u2019s Holy One. What do you want with us? Have you
        come to destroy us already?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:34
        content: '  This is an assertive statement made by the demon to Jesus.    '
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Immediately the demon hurled the man down on the floor in front of
        them. But Jesus rebuked the demon, <JESUS>\u201CBe quiet and come out of
        him!\u201D</JESUS> And without causing him any harm, the demon came out of
        him."
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Great astonishment swept over the people, and they said among themselves,
        \u201CWhat kind of man is this who has such power and authority? With a mere
        word, he commands demons to come out, and they obey him!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: Jesus Heals Many'
      title: Jesus Heals Many
      number: 37
      content: Reports about Jesus spread like wildfire throughout every community
        in the surrounding region.
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "After leaving the synagogue, Jesus went into Simon\u2019s house,
        where Simon\u2019s mother-in-law was sick with a high fever. The disciples
        begged Jesus to help her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: Jesus stood over her and rebuked the fever, [[COMMENT(0)]] and she
        was healed instantly. Then she got up and began to serve them.
      comments:
      - number: 4:39
        content: '  Five times in this chapter, Jesus corrects and rebukes various
          things and persons. He rebuked Satan (v.  ) and the unbelieving people
          in his hometown (vv.  ). Twice he rebuked demons (vv.    and  ). And in
          this verse, he rebukes fever.    '
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: At sunset, [[COMMENT(0)]] the people brought all those who were sick
        to Jesus to be healed. Jesus laid his hands on them one by one, and he healed
        them all of different illnesses.
      comments:
      - number: 4:40
        content: '  People came before dark. The Sabbath, which was to be a day of
          rest for every Jew, began at sunset on Friday and ended at sunset on Saturday.    '
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Demons also came out of many of them. Knowing that Jesus was the
        Anointed One, the demons shouted while coming out, \u201CYou are the Messiah,
        the Son of El Shaddai!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] But Jesus rebuked them and commanded
        them to be silent."
      comments:
      - number: 4:41
        content: "  Or \u201CSon of God.\u201D    is used to emphasize the Hebraic
          word for God Almighty. See footnote on  .    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'At daybreak the next morning, the crowds came and searched everywhere
        for him, but Jesus had already left to go to a secluded place. When they
        finally found him, they held him tightly, begging him to stay with them in
        Capernaum. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "But Jesus said, <JESUS>\u201CDon\u2019t you know there are other
        places I must go and offer the hope of God\u2019s kingdom?</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>This is what I have been sent to do.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:43
        content: "  The gospel includes the hope of an eternal kingdom. Conversion
          is more than believing a historical event but is found in the revelation
          of God\u2019s kingdom realm that changes our hearts.  "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: Jesus continued to travel and preach in the synagogues throughout
        the land.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Miracle Catch of Fish'
      title: The Miracle Catch of Fish
      number: 1
      content: 'On one occasion, Jesus was preaching to a crowd on the shore of Lake
        Galilee. [[COMMENT(0)]] A vast multitude of people was pushing to get close
        to Jesus to hear the word of God. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:1
        content: "  Or \u201CGennesaret,\u201D which is known as Lake Galilee.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He noticed two fishing boats at the water\u2019s edge, with the fishermen
        nearby, rinsing their nets. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Jesus climbed into the boat belonging to Simon Peter and said to
        him, <JESUS>\u201CLet me use your boat. Push it off a short distance away
        from the shore so I can speak to the crowd.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Jesus sat down and taught the people from the boat. When he had finished,
        he said to Peter, <JESUS>\u201CNow row out to deep water to cast your nets
        and you will have a great catch.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CMaster,\u201D Peter replied, \u201Cwe\u2019ve just come back
        from fishing all night and didn\u2019t catch a thing. But if you insist,
        we\u2019ll go out again and let down our nets because of your word.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When they pulled up their nets, they were shocked to see a huge catch
        of fish, and their nets were ready to burst! '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: They waved to their business partners in the other boat for help.
        They ended up completely filling both boats with fish until they began to
        sink! [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 5:7
        content: "  It has been estimated that this was a catch of nearly one ton
          of fish, what was typically caught in two weeks\u2019 time. The miracle
          is even greater when we consider that fishing was normally only done at
          night.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "When Simon Peter saw this astonishing miracle, he knelt at Jesus\u2019
        feet and begged him, \u201CGo away from me, Master, for I am a sinful man!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: "Simon Peter and the other fishermen\u2014including his fishing partners,
        Jacob [[COMMENT(0)]] and John, the sons of Zebedee\u2014were awestruck over
        the miracle catch of fish.Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CDo not yield to your
        fear, Simon Peter. From now on, you will catch men for salvation!\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "5:9\u201310"
        content: "  Or \u201CJames.\u201D Both Greek and Aramaic leave the Hebrew
          name as it is, Jacob. This translation will use Jacob throughout.     
          Translated from the Aramaic text. The Greek word    is a compound word
          of    (meaning \u201Clife\u201D) and    (meaning \u201Cto catch\u201D).
          Fishermen catch fish that die and are consumed, but Peter was to catch
          men and give them life and freedom.    "
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: "Simon Peter and the other fishermen\u2014including his fishing partners,
        Jacob [[COMMENT(0)]] and John, the sons of Zebedee\u2014were awestruck over
        the miracle catch of fish.Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CDo not yield to your
        fear, Simon Peter. From now on, you will catch men for salvation!\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "5:9\u201310"
        content: "  Or \u201CJames.\u201D Both Greek and Aramaic leave the Hebrew
          name as it is, Jacob. This translation will use Jacob throughout.     
          Translated from the Aramaic text. The Greek word    is a compound word
          of    (meaning \u201Clife\u201D) and    (meaning \u201Cto catch\u201D).
          Fishermen catch fish that die and are consumed, but Peter was to catch
          men and give them life and freedom.    "
    - name: '11: Jesus, the Healer'
      title: Jesus, the Healer
      number: 11
      content: After pulling their boats to the shore, they left everything behind
        and followed Jesus. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 5:11
        content: '  When you leave everything behind to follow Jesus, you are actually
          in the position to have it all. Jesus will be your everything. Later, Peter
          will once again leave his nets behind to swim to Jesus. See  .    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "One day, while Jesus was in a certain city, he came upon a man covered
        with leprous sores. When the man recognized Jesus, he fell on his face at
        Jesus\u2019 feet and begged to be healed, saying, \u201CIf you were willing,
        you could completely heal me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Jesus reached out and touched him [[COMMENT(0)]] and said, <JESUS>\u201COf
        course I am willing to heal you, and now you will be healed.\u201D</JESUS>
        Instantly, the leprous sores were healed, and his skin became smooth.Jesus
        said, <JESUS>\u201CTell no one what has happened, but go to the temple priests
        and show them you\u2019ve been healed. And to show that you are purified,
        make an offering for your cleansing, just as Moses commanded. You will become
        a living testimony to them!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: "5:13\u201314"
        content: '  For the religious Jew, touching a leper was forbidden because
          of the contamination. Jesus was not defiled in touching the leper; rather,
          the leper was healed.    '
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Jesus reached out and touched him [[COMMENT(0)]] and said, <JESUS>\u201COf
        course I am willing to heal you, and now you will be healed.\u201D</JESUS>
        Instantly, the leprous sores were healed, and his skin became smooth.Jesus
        said, <JESUS>\u201CTell no one what has happened, but go to the temple priests
        and show them you\u2019ve been healed. And to show that you are purified,
        make an offering for your cleansing, just as Moses commanded. You will become
        a living testimony to them!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: "5:13\u201314"
        content: '  For the religious Jew, touching a leper was forbidden because
          of the contamination. Jesus was not defiled in touching the leper; rather,
          the leper was healed.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'After this miracle, the news about Jesus spread even farther. Massive
        crowds continually gathered to hear him speak and to be healed from their
        illnesses. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: But Jesus often slipped away from them and went into the wilderness
        to pray.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: One day, many Jewish religious leaders known as Pharisees, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        along with many religious scholars, came from every village in Galilee, throughout
        Judea, and even from Jerusalem to hear Jesus teach. And the power of the
        Lord God surged through him to instantly heal the sick.
      comments:
      - number: 5:17
        content: "  \u201CPharisees\u201D means \u201Cseparated ones.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Some men came to Jesus, carrying a paraplegic man on a stretcher.
        They attempted to bring him in past the crowd to set him down in front of
        Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: But because there were so many people crowding the door, they had
        no way to bring him inside. So they crawled onto the roof, dug their way
        through the roof tiles, and lowered the man, stretcher and all, into the
        middle of the crowd, right in front of Jesus.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Seeing the demonstration of their faith, Jesus said to the paraplegic
        man, <JESUS>\u201CMy friend, your sins are forgiven!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "The Jewish religious leaders and the religious scholars [[COMMENT(0)]]
        whispered objections among themselves. \u201CWho does this man think he is
        to speak such blasphemy? Only God can forgive sins! Does he think he is God?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 5:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cscribes.\u201D They were the experts in the law of Moses.    "
    - name: '22-23: '
      title: 
      number: 22-23
      content: "Jesus, knowing their thoughts, said to them, <JESUS>\u201CWhy do
        you argue in your hearts over what I do and think that it is blasphemy for
        me to say his sins are forgiven? Let me ask you, which is easier to prove:
        when I say, \u2018Your sins are forgiven,\u2019 or when I say, \u2018Stand
        up, carry your stretcher, and walk\u2019?\u201D</JESUS>Jesus turned to the
        paraplegic man and said, "
      comments: []
    - name: '22-23: '
      title: 
      number: 22-23
      content: "Jesus, knowing their thoughts, said to them, <JESUS>\u201CWhy do
        you argue in your hearts over what I do and think that it is blasphemy for
        me to say his sins are forgiven? Let me ask you, which is easier to prove:
        when I say, \u2018Your sins are forgiven,\u2019 or when I say, \u2018Stand
        up, carry your stretcher, and walk\u2019?\u201D</JESUS>Jesus turned to the
        paraplegic man and said, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CTo prove to you all that I, the Son of Man,</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>have the lawful authority on earth to forgive sins,
        I say to you now, stand up! Carry your stretcher and go on home, for you
        are healed.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 5:24
        content: "  This is the title Jesus uses for himself more than any other,
          especially in Luke. This refers to the vision of Daniel when he saw the
          Ancient of Days, and walking before the Ancient of Days was one like the
          Son of Man who would be given the right to judge the world. Calling himself
          the Son of Man was Jesus\u2019 claim to heavenly authority. It was more
          of an exalted and heavenly concept than being a human, the \u201Cson of
          a man.\u201D See  ;  .    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: In an instant, the man rose right before their eyes. He stood, picked
        up his stretcher, and went home, giving God the glory with every step he
        took.
      comments: []
    - name: '26: Jesus Calls Matthew to Follow Him'
      title: Jesus Calls Matthew to Follow Him
      number: 26
      content: "The people were seized with astonishment and dumbfounded over what
        they had just witnessed. And they all praised God, remarking over and over,
        \u201CIncredible! What an unbelievable miracle [[COMMENT(0)]] we\u2019ve
        seen today!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 5:26
        content: "  Or \u201Cthings we never expected,\u201D or \u201Cparadox.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Afterward, Jesus went out and looked for a man named Matthew. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He found him sitting at his tax booth, for he was a tax collector. Jesus
        said to him, <JESUS>\u201CBe my disciple and follow me.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 5:27
        content: "  The Greek text is \u201CLevi,\u201D another name for Matthew.    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: That very moment, Matthew got up, left everything behind, and followed
        him.
      comments: []
    - name: '29-30: '
      title: 
      number: 29-30
      content: "Matthew wanted to throw a banquet to honor Jesus. So he invited Jesus
        to his home for dinner, along with many of Levi\u2019s fellow tax collectors
        and other guests. But the Jewish religious leaders and experts of the law
        complained to Jesus\u2019 disciples, \u201CWhy would you defile yourselves
        by eating and drinking with tax collectors and sinners? Doesn\u2019t Jesus
        know it\u2019s wrong to do that?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29-30: '
      title: 
      number: 29-30
      content: "Matthew wanted to throw a banquet to honor Jesus. So he invited Jesus
        to his home for dinner, along with many of Levi\u2019s fellow tax collectors
        and other guests. But the Jewish religious leaders and experts of the law
        complained to Jesus\u2019 disciples, \u201CWhy would you defile yourselves
        by eating and drinking with tax collectors and sinners? Doesn\u2019t Jesus
        know it\u2019s wrong to do that?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Jesus overheard their complaining and said, <JESUS>\u201CWho goes
        to the doctor for a cure? Those who are well or those who are sick?</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 5:31
        content: "  The word used here is the Greek word for \u201Cevil.\u201D Sickness
          is a form of evil in God\u2019s eyes. Jesus came to heal the \u201Cevil\u201D
          or sicknesses of earth.    "
    - name: '32: A Question about Fasting'
      title: A Question about Fasting
      number: 32
      content: "<JESUS>I have not come to call the \u2018righteous,\u2019 but to
        call those who know they are sinners and bring them to repentance.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Jesus\u2019 critics questioned him. \u201CJohn the prophet is known
        for leading his disciples to fast often and pray. As the religious leaders
        of the land, we do the same. Why do you and your disciples spend most of
        your time feasting at banquets?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 5:33
        content: '  It is likely that Matthew held his banquet on one of the Jewish
          fast days.    '
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Jesus replied, <JESUS>\u201CShould you make the sons of the bridal
        chamber fast while celebrating with the Bridegroom?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "<JESUS>But when the Bridegroom is taken away from them, then you
        will see them fasting.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "And he gave them this illustration: <JESUS>\u201CNo one rips up a
        new garment to make patches for an old, worn-out one. If you tear up the
        new to make a patch for the old, it would not match the old garment.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: '<JESUS>And who pours new wine into an old wineskin? If someone did,
        the old wineskin would burst and the new wine would be lost.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: '<JESUS>New wine must always be poured into new wineskins.</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 5:38
        content: '  Christ is our new garment (righteousness) and our new wine that
          is poured into a new wineskin (our new life and divine nature). Many today
          are trying to patch up their old garments (self-righteousness), hoping
          their old lives can hold the new wine of the Spirit.  '
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "<JESUS>Yet you say, \u2018The old ways are better,\u2019 and you
        refuse to even taste the new wine that I bring.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jesus and Religious Traditions'
      title: Jesus and Religious Traditions
      number: 1
      content: 'One Sabbath day, Jesus and his disciples were walking through a field
        of ripe wheat. His disciples plucked some heads of grain, rubbed the husks
        off with their hands, and ate them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "This infuriated some of the Jewish religious leaders. They said to
        Jesus, \u201CWhy are you allowing your disciples to harvest grain on the
        Sabbath? Don\u2019t you know it\u2019s not permissible according to the law?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Jesus replied, <JESUS>\u201CHaven\u2019t you read the Scriptures?
        Haven\u2019t you read what King David did when he was hungry?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "<JESUS>He entered the sanctuary of God, took the bread of God\u2019s
        presence right off the sacred table, and shared it with his men.</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>It was only lawful for the priests to eat the bread
        of God\u2019s presence.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 6:4
        content: "  This incident is found in  . Jesus referred to this story to
          prove to the Pharisees that they were hypocrites who were willing to overlook
          David\u2019s \u201Cviolation\u201D of the Sabbath but not Jesus\u2019 supposed
          violation.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "<JESUS>You need to know that the Son of Man is no slave to the Sabbath,
        for I am master over the Sabbath.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: On another Sabbath, Jesus was teaching in the synagogue. In the room
        with him was a man with a deformed right hand. Everyone watched Jesus closely,
        especially the Jewish religious leaders and the religious scholars, to see
        if Jesus would heal on a Sabbath, for they were eager to find a reason to
        accuse him of breaking the Jewish laws.
      comments: []
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: On another Sabbath, Jesus was teaching in the synagogue. In the room
        with him was a man with a deformed right hand. Everyone watched Jesus closely,
        especially the Jewish religious leaders and the religious scholars, to see
        if Jesus would heal on a Sabbath, for they were eager to find a reason to
        accuse him of breaking the Jewish laws.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Jesus, knowing their every thought, said to the man with the deformed
        hand, <JESUS>\u201CCome and stand here in the middle of the room.\u201D</JESUS>
        So he got up and came forward."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Jesus said to all who were there, <JESUS>\u201CLet me ask you a question.
        Which is better: to heal or to do harm on the Sabbath? I have come to save
        a life, but you have come to find a life to destroy.\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 6:9
        content: "  Jesus knew there were some present who wanted to \u201Cdestroy\u201D
          his life and would soon crucify him. He came to heal; they came to kill.
          They were the real Sabbath breakers.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "One by one Jesus looked into the eyes of each person in the room.
        Then he said to the man, <JESUS>\u201CStretch out your arm and open your
        hand!\u201D</JESUS>With everyone watching intently, he stretched out his
        arm, and his hand was completely healed!"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Jesus Chooses Twelve Apostles'
      title: Jesus Chooses Twelve Apostles
      number: 11
      content: The room erupted with bitter rage, and from that moment on, the religious
        leaders plotted among themselves about how they might harm Jesus.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'After leaving the synagogue, Jesus went into the high hills to spend
        the whole night in prayer to God. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 6:12
        content: '  This was the pattern of Jesus in the Gospel accounts. Before
          he made important decisions and before great events in his life, he sought
          his Father. Once he saw what the Father wanted, Jesus obeyed as the perfect
          Son. See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: At daybreak, he called together all of his followers and selected
        twelve from among them, and he appointed them to be his apostles. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 6:13
        content: "  Apostle means \u201Cambassador,\u201D \u201Cmissionary,\u201D
          or \u201Csent one.\u201D The apostles were all different in their personalities
          and came from different backgrounds. The people Jesus chooses today don\u2019t
          all look, act, or sound alike. The first ministry Jesus established was
          the apostolic. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '14-16: '
      title: 
      number: 14-16
      content: "Here are their names: Simon, whom he named Peter; Andrew, Peter\u2019s
        brother; Jacob; John; Philip; Bartholomew; [[COMMENT(0)]] Matthew; Thomas;
        Jacob the son of Alpheus; Simon, known as a fiery political zealot; Judah 
        the son of Jacob; and Judas the locksmith,  who later betrayed Jesus."
      comments:
      - number: "6:14\u201316"
        content: "  Many scholars believe that Bartholomew was the Nathaniel mentioned
          in  .      He is also called Thaddeus, as mentioned in    and  .      The
          name Judas is actually Judah. Iscariot is not his last name, but could
          be taken from the name of the town, Kerioth, twelve miles south of Hebron.
          More plausibly, it is from a Hebrew word meaning \u201Clock\u201D: Judah
          the locksmith. Most likely he was chosen to lock the collection bag, which
          means he had the key and could pilfer the funds at will. Sadly, he wanted
          to lock up Jesus and control him for his own ends.    "
    - name: '14-16: '
      title: 
      number: 14-16
      content: "Here are their names: Simon, whom he named Peter; Andrew, Peter\u2019s
        brother; Jacob; John; Philip; Bartholomew; [[COMMENT(0)]] Matthew; Thomas;
        Jacob the son of Alpheus; Simon, known as a fiery political zealot; Judah 
        the son of Jacob; and Judas the locksmith,  who later betrayed Jesus."
      comments:
      - number: "6:14\u201316"
        content: "  Many scholars believe that Bartholomew was the Nathaniel mentioned
          in  .      He is also called Thaddeus, as mentioned in    and  .      The
          name Judas is actually Judah. Iscariot is not his last name, but could
          be taken from the name of the town, Kerioth, twelve miles south of Hebron.
          More plausibly, it is from a Hebrew word meaning \u201Clock\u201D: Judah
          the locksmith. Most likely he was chosen to lock the collection bag, which
          means he had the key and could pilfer the funds at will. Sadly, he wanted
          to lock up Jesus and control him for his own ends.    "
    - name: '14-16: '
      title: 
      number: 14-16
      content: "Here are their names: Simon, whom he named Peter; Andrew, Peter\u2019s
        brother; Jacob; John; Philip; Bartholomew; [[COMMENT(0)]] Matthew; Thomas;
        Jacob the son of Alpheus; Simon, known as a fiery political zealot; Judah 
        the son of Jacob; and Judas the locksmith,  who later betrayed Jesus."
      comments:
      - number: "6:14\u201316"
        content: "  Many scholars believe that Bartholomew was the Nathaniel mentioned
          in  .      He is also called Thaddeus, as mentioned in    and  .      The
          name Judas is actually Judah. Iscariot is not his last name, but could
          be taken from the name of the town, Kerioth, twelve miles south of Hebron.
          More plausibly, it is from a Hebrew word meaning \u201Clock\u201D: Judah
          the locksmith. Most likely he was chosen to lock the collection bag, which
          means he had the key and could pilfer the funds at will. Sadly, he wanted
          to lock up Jesus and control him for his own ends.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Jesus and his apostles came down from the hillside to a level field,
        where a large number of his disciples waited, along with a massive crowd:
        people from all over Judea, Jerusalem, and the coastal district of Tyre and
        Sidon. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 6:17
        content: '  The non-Jewish people flocked to hear Jesus, and he healed them
          all.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'They had all come to listen to the Word so that they could be healed
        of their diseases [[COMMENT(0)]] and be set free from tormenting demonic
        powers. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:18
        content: '  This is the literal translation of the Aramaic text.    '
    - name: '19: Jesus Taught Them What Matters Most'
      title: Jesus Taught Them What Matters Most
      number: 19
      content: The entire crowd eagerly tried to come near Jesus, to touch him to
        receive healing, because a tangible, supernatural power emanated from him
        and healed all who came close to him.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Looking intently at his followers, Jesus began his sermon. <JESUS>\u201CHow
        enriched</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>you become when you are a beggar,
        for you will experience the reality of God\u2019s kingdom.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 6:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cblessed.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CHow filled you become when you are consumed with hunger
        and desire, for you will be completely satisfied.</JESUS><JESUS>\u201CHow
        content you become when you weep</JESUS>  <JESUS>with complete brokenness</JESUS><JESUS>,
        for you will laugh with unrestrained joy.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CHow favored you become when you are hated, excommunicated,
        or slandered, or when your name is spoken of as evil because of your love
        for me, the Son of Man.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CI promise you that as you experience these things, you
        will celebrate and dance with overflowing joy, and the heavenly reward of
        your faith will be abundant, because you are being treated the same way as
        your forefathers the prophets.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CBut what sorrows await those of you who are rich in
        this life only, for you have already received all the comfort you\u2019ll
        ever get.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CWhat sorrows await those of you who are content with
        yourselves, for hunger and emptiness will come to you.</JESUS><JESUS>\u201CWhat
        sorrows await those of you who laugh now, having received all your joy in
        this life only, for grief and wailing will come to you.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: Love Your Enemies'
      title: Love Your Enemies
      number: 26
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CWhat sorrows await those of you who are always honored
        and lauded by others, for that\u2019s how your forefathers treated every
        false prophet.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CBut I say to you who hear, love your enemies and do
        something wonderful</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>for them in return for
        their hatred.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 6:27
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic text.    '
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: '<JESUS>When someone curses you, bless that person in return. When
        others mistreat and harass you, accept it as your mission to pray for them.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: '<JESUS>To those who despise you, continue to serve them and minister
        to them.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>If someone takes away your coat,
        give him as a gift your shirt as well.</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 6:29
        content: "  As literally translated from the Aramaic text. The Greek text
          states, \u201CIf someone strikes you on one side of your jaw, offer the
          other side too.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: '<JESUS>When someone comes to beg from you, give to that person what
        you have. When things are wrongly taken from you, do not demand they be given
        back.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: <JESUS>The way you want others to treat you is how you should treat
        everyone else.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CAre you really showing true love by loving only those
        who love you? Even those who don\u2019t know God will do that.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "<JESUS>Are you really showing compassion when you do good deeds only
        to those who do good deeds to you? Even those who don\u2019t know God will
        do that.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CIf you lend money only to those you know will repay
        you, what credit is that to your character? Even those who don\u2019t know
        God do that.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "<JESUS>Rather love your enemies and continue to treat them well.
        When you lend money, don\u2019t despair</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>if
        you are never paid back, for it is not lost. You will receive a rich reward
        and you will be known as true children of the Most High God, having his same
        nature. Be like your Father who is famous for his kindness to heal</JESUS>   
        <JESUS>even the thankless and cruel.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 6:35
        content: "  The Aramaic is literally \u201CDo not cut off the hope of man.\u201D     
          Literal translation of the Aramaic text.    "
    - name: '36: Judging Others'
      title: Judging Others
      number: 36
      content: "<JESUS>Overflow with mercy and compassion for others, just as your
        heavenly Father overflows with mercy and compassion for all.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Jesus said, <JESUS>\u201CForsake the habit of criticizing and judging
        others, and you will not be criticized and judged in return. Don\u2019t condemn
        others and you will not be condemned. Forgive over and over, and you will
        be forgiven over and over.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "<JESUS>Give generously and generous gifts will be given back to you,
        shaken down to make room for more. Abundant gifts will pour out upon you
        with such an overflowing measure that it will run over the top! The measurement
        of your generosity becomes the measurement of your return.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Jesus also quoted these proverbs: <JESUS>\u201CWhat happens when
        a blind man pretends to guide another blind man? They both stumble into a
        ditch!</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: '<JESUS>And how could the apprentice know more than his master, for
        only after he is fully qualified will he be at that level.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "<JESUS>Why do you focus on the flaw in someone else\u2019s life and
        fail to notice the glaring flaws of your own life?</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 6:41
        content: "  Or \u201CWhy do you see a speck in your brother\u2019s eye but
          fail to see the beam of wood sticking out of your own eye?\u201D    "
    - name: '42: The Fruit of Your Life'
      title: The Fruit of Your Life
      number: 42
      content: "<JESUS>How could you say to your friend, \u2018Here, let me show
        you where you\u2019re wrong,\u2019 when you are guilty of even more than
        he? You are overly critical, splitting hairs and being a hypocrite! You must
        acknowledge your own blind spots and deal with them before you will be able
        to deal with the blind spot of your friend.\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 6:42
        content: "  Or \u201CYou hypocrite, why don\u2019t you first remove the beam
          sticking out of your own eye? Then you can see clearly to remove the small
          speck out of your brother\u2019s eye.\u201D Jesus is teaching that our
          blind spots prevent us from accurately evaluating the needs of others.    "
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CYou\u2019ll never find choice fruit hanging on a bad,
        unhealthy tree. And rotten fruit doesn\u2019t hang on a good, healthy tree.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: '<JESUS>Every tree will be revealed by the quality of fruit that it
        produces. You will never pick figs or grapes from thorn trees.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: <JESUS>People are known in this same way. Out of the virtue stored
        in their hearts, good and upright people will produce good fruit. Likewise,
        out of the evil hidden in their hearts, evil ones will produce what is evil.
        For the overflow of what has been stored in your heart will be seen by your
        fruit and will be heard in your words.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CWhat good does it do for you to say I am your Lord and
        Master if you don\u2019t put into practice what I teach you?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: '<JESUS>Let me describe the one who truly follows me and does what
        I say:</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: '<JESUS>He is like a man who chooses the right place to build a house
        and then lays a deep and secure foundation. When the storms and floods rage
        against that house, it continues to stand strong and unshaken through the
        tempest, for he built it wisely on the right foundation.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "<JESUS>But the one who has heard my teaching and does not obey it
        is like a man who builds a house without laying any foundation at all. When
        the storms and floods rage against that house, it will immediately collapse
        and become a total loss.</JESUS>  <JESUS>Which of these two builders will
        you be?</JESUS><JESUS>\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 6:49
        content: '  This last question is an important summary implied in the context.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jesus Heals'
      title: Jesus Heals
      number: 1
      content: 'After Jesus finished giving revelation [[COMMENT(0)]] to the people
        on the hillside, he went on to Capernaum. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cteaching.\u201D The Greek word used here is  .    "
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: 'A Roman military captain there had a beloved servant whom he valued
        highly, and who was sick to the point of death. When the captain heard that
        Jesus was in the city, he sent some respected Jewish elders to plead with
        him to come and heal his dying servant. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: 'A Roman military captain there had a beloved servant whom he valued
        highly, and who was sick to the point of death. When the captain heard that
        Jesus was in the city, he sent some respected Jewish elders to plead with
        him to come and heal his dying servant. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "So they came to Jesus and told him, \u201CThe Roman captain is a
        wonderful man. If anyone deserves a visit from you, it is him. Won\u2019t
        you please come to his home and heal his servant? "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "For he loves the Jewish people, and he even built our meeting hall
        for us.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: "Jesus started off with them, but on his way there, friends of the
        captain stopped him and delivered this message: \u201CMaster, don\u2019t
        bother to come to me in person, for I am not good enough for you to enter
        my home. I\u2019m not worthy enough to even come out to meet one like you.
        But if you would just speak the word of healing from right where you are,
        I know that my servant will be healed."
      comments: []
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: "Jesus started off with them, but on his way there, friends of the
        captain stopped him and delivered this message: \u201CMaster, don\u2019t
        bother to come to me in person, for I am not good enough for you to enter
        my home. I\u2019m not worthy enough to even come out to meet one like you.
        But if you would just speak the word of healing from right where you are,
        I know that my servant will be healed."
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "I am an ordinary man. Yet I understand the power of authority, and
        I see that authority operating through you. I have soldiers under me who
        obey everything I command. I also have authorities over me whom I likewise
        obey. So Master, just speak the word and healing will flow.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Jesus marveled at this. He turned around and said to the crowd who
        had followed him, <JESUS>\u201CListen, everyone! Never have I found among
        the people of God a man like this who believes so strongly in me.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: Jesus Raises the Dead'
      title: Jesus Raises the Dead
      number: 10
      content: "Jesus then spoke the healing word from a distance. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        When the man\u2019s friends returned to the home, they found the servant
        completely healed and doing fine."
      comments:
      - number: 7:10
        content: '  Implicit in the miracle was that Jesus released the word of healing
          for the servant.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Shortly afterward, Jesus left on a journey to the village of Nain,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] with a massive crowd of people following him, and his disciples. '
      comments:
      - number: 7:11
        content: "    means \u201Cpleasant.\u201D The Prince of Life was about to
          enter the gate of the city when death came out. There at the gates where
          life and death meet, life wins and death is defeated. Just outside of Jerusalem
          one day, death and life met again, and life won forevermore.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "As he approached the village, he met a multitude of people in a funeral
        procession, who were mourning as they carried the body of a young man to
        the cemetery. The boy was his mother\u2019s only son, and she was a widow. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When the Lord saw the grieving mother, his heart broke for her. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        With great tenderness he said to her, <JESUS>\u201CPlease don\u2019t cry.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:13
        content: "  The Greek word    denotes the deepest level of compassion. There
          is no greater word in the Greek language to describe the depth of emotion
          Jesus felt for this widow over the loss of her son.    is actually the
          word for \u201Cintestines.\u201D Jesus\u2019 emotions fully identified
          with her grief and he carried her sorrow.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then he stepped up to the coffin and touched it. When the pallbearers
        came to a halt, Jesus spoke directly to the corpse, <JESUS>\u201CYoung man,
        I say to you, arise and live!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Immediately, the young man moved, sat up, and spoke to those nearby.
        Jesus presented the son to his mother, alive! '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "A tremendous sense of holy mystery swept over the crowd. They shouted
        praises to God, saying, \u201CGod himself has blessed us by visiting his
        people! A great prophet has appeared among us!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: "17: The Prophet John\u2019s Question"
      title: "The Prophet John\u2019s Question"
      number: 17
      content: The news of Jesus and this miracle raced throughout Judea and the
        entire surrounding region.
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "John\u2019s disciples reported to him in prison  [[COMMENT(0)]] about
        all the wonderful miracles and the works Jesus was doing. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:18
        content: '  See also  ;  .    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'So John dispatched two of his disciples to go and inquire of Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When they came before the Master, they asked him, \u201CAre you the
        coming Messiah we\u2019ve been expecting, or are we to continue to look for
        someone else? John the prophet has sent us to you to seek your answer.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: Without answering, [[COMMENT(0)]] Jesus turned to the crowd and healed
        many of their incurable diseases. His miracle power freed many from their
        suffering. He restored the gift of sight to the blind, and he drove out demonic
        spirits from those who were tormented.
      comments:
      - number: 7:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cat that time.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Only then did Jesus answer the question posed by John\u2019s disciples.
        <JESUS>\u201CNow go back and tell John what you have just seen and heard
        here today. The blind are now seeing. The crippled are now walking. Those
        who were lepers are now cured. Those who were deaf are now hearing. Those
        who were dead are now brought back to life. The poor and broken</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>are given the hope of salvation.</JESUS>    "
      comments:
      - number: 7:22
        content: '  This fulfills many Old Testament references to the coming of
          the Messiah, including  ;  ;  .      Jesus is assuring John that the message
          he brings is life and salvation, not judgment and wrath.    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "<JESUS>And tell John these words: \u2018The blessing of heaven comes
        upon those who never lose their faith</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>in
        me, no matter what happens.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 7:23
        content: "  The Greek text is literally \u201CBlessed are those who are not
          offended over me.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "After John\u2019s messengers departed, Jesus spoke about John to
        the audience crowded around him, saying, <JESUS>\u201CWhat kind of man did
        you expect to see out in the wilderness? Did you expect to see a man who
        would be easily influenced and shaken by the shifting opinions of others?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: '<JESUS>Who did you go there to see? Did you expect to see a man decked
        out in the splendid fashion of the day</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>living
        in the lap of luxury?</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 7:25
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: '<JESUS>Or did you discover a true prophet out in the lonely wilderness?
        Yes, John was a legitimate prophet. Even more than that,</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "<JESUS>he was the fulfillment of this Scripture:</JESUS><JESUS>\u2018See,
        I am sending my prophetic messenger</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>who will
        go ahead of me</JESUS><JESUS>to prepare hearts to receive me.\u2019</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:27
        content: "  Or \u201Cangel.\u201D      This is quoted from  .    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CThroughout history there was never found a man as great
        as John. Yet those who now walk in God\u2019s kingdom realm, though they
        appear to be insignificant, will become even greater than he.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "When the common and disreputable people among the audience heard
        Jesus say this, they acknowledged that it was the truth, for they had already
        experienced John\u2019s baptism. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: But the hearts of the Jewish religious leaders and experts of the
        law had rejected the clear purpose of God by refusing to be baptized by John.
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Jesus continued, saying, <JESUS>\u201CHow could I describe the people
        of this generation? Can\u2019t you see?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "<JESUS>You\u2019re like children playing games on the playground,
        complaining to friends, \u2018You don\u2019t like it when we want to play
        Wedding. And you don\u2019t like it when we want to play Funeral. Why will
        you neither dance nor mourn?\u2019</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:32
        content: "  Both Christ and John the Baptist offered people the \u201Cwedding,\u201D
          but the Pharisees didn\u2019t want to dance. Both offered a funeral to
          the old, dead ways of religion, but the Pharisees refused to attend. Grace
          offered them salvation, but they rejected it.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CWhen the prophet John came fasting and refused to drink
        wine, you said, \u2018He\u2019s crazy! There\u2019s a demon in him.\u2019</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "<JESUS>Yet when the Son of Man came feasting and drinking, you said,
        \u2018Look at this man! He is nothing but a glutton and a drunkard. He spends
        all his time with tax collectors and other notorious sinners.\u2019</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: Extravagant Worship'
      title: Extravagant Worship
      number: 35
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CNevertheless, the wisdom of God</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>will be proven true by the expressions of godliness in everyone who
        follows me.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 7:35
        content: "  Or \u201CWisdom is vindicated by all her children.\u201D The
          Aramaic word used here is a homonym that means either \u201Cchildren\u201D
          or \u201Cgood works\u201D (expressions of godliness). This may explain
          why there is such a variation of the Greek texts.    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Afterward Simeon, [[COMMENT(0)]] a Jewish religious leader, asked
        Jesus to his home for dinner. Jesus accepted the invitation. When he went
        to Simeon\u2019s home, he took his place at the table."
      comments:
      - number: 7:36
        content: '  The name Simeon is supplied from v.  .    '
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "In the neighborhood there was an immoral woman of the streets, known
        to all to be a prostitute. When she heard that Jesus was at Simeon\u2019s
        house, she took an exquisite flask made from alabaster, [[COMMENT(0)]] filled
        it with the most expensive perfume, went right into the home of the Jewish
        religious leader, and in front of all the guests, she knelt at the feet of
        Jesus. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:37
        content: '  This is a soft, cream-colored stone often used for jars and vases.    '
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Broken and weeping, she covered his feet with the tears that fell
        from her face. She kept crying and drying his feet with her long hair. Over
        and over she kissed Jesus\u2019 feet. Then, as an act of worship, she opened
        her flask and anointed his feet [[COMMENT(0)]] with her costly perfume."
      comments:
      - number: 7:38
        content: "  Six times in Luke we find someone at Jesus\u2019 feet (described
          as \u201Cbeautiful\u201D in  ): (1) the sinful woman mentioned in this
          verse who poured out her worship and tears at Jesus\u2019 feet; (2) the
          demonized man who worshiped at Jesus\u2019 feet (); (3) Jairus, who fell
          at his feet pleading for a miracle for his daughter (); (4) Mary, who sat
          at his feet and received his word (); (5) the healed leper who fell at
          his feet in deep gratitude (); (6) those who worshiped Jesus at his resurrection
          when he showed them his hands and his feet ().    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "When Simeon saw what was happening, he thought, \u201CThis man can\u2019t
        be a true prophet. If he were really a prophet, he would know what kind of
        sinful woman is touching him.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:39
        content: '  Simeon thought Jesus should have known the sinfulness of the
          woman, but Simeon should have known the love of the one next to him, who
          was ready to forgive and restore. Religion focuses on the sinfulness of
          a person, but faith sees the glory of the one who forgives and heals.    '
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "Jesus said, <JESUS>\u201CSimeon, I have a word for you.\u201D</JESUS>\u201CGo
        ahead, Teacher. I want to hear it,\u201D he answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CIt\u2019s a story about two men who were deeply in debt.
        One owed the bank one hundred thousand dollars,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>and the other only owed ten thousand dollars.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:41
        content: "  The Greek text uses the monetary term  . The point is that one
          person owed more than a year\u2019s wages, the other much less.    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "<JESUS>When it was obvious that neither of them would be able to
        repay their debts, the kind banker graciously wrote off the debts and forgave
        them all that they owed. Tell me, Simeon, which of the two debtors would
        be more thankful? Which one would love the banker most?\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Simeon answered, \u201CI suppose it would be the one with the greater
        debt forgiven.\u201D<JESUS>\u201CYou\u2019re right,\u201D</JESUS> Jesus agreed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "Then he spoke to Simeon about the woman still weeping at his feet.<JESUS>\u201CDo
        you see this woman kneeling here? She is doing for me what you didn\u2019t
        bother to do. When I entered your home as your guest, you didn\u2019t think
        about offering me water to wash the dust off my feet. Yet she came into your
        home and washed my feet with her many tears and then dried my feet with her
        hair.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "<JESUS>You didn\u2019t even welcome me into your home with the customary
        kiss of greeting, but from the moment I came in she has not stopped kissing
        my feet.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "<JESUS>You didn\u2019t take the time to anoint my head with fragrant
        oil, but she anointed my head and feet with the finest perfume.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "<JESUS>She has been forgiven of all her many sins. This is why she
        has shown me such extravagant love. But those who assume they have very little
        to be forgiven will love me very little.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "Then Jesus said to the woman at his feet, <JESUS>\u201C</JESUS><JESUS>All</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>your sins are forgiven.\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:48
        content: "  Twice in Luke\u2019s Gospel we hear Jesus say, \u201CAll your
          sins are forgiven.\u201D Once he says it to a man () and here to a woman.
          The proof of her sins being forgiven is her love; with the healed man it
          was his life, for he took up his bed and walked.  "
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "All the dinner guests said among themselves, \u201CWho is the one
        who can even forgive sins?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: "Then Jesus said to the woman, <JESUS>\u201CYour faith in me has given
        you life. Now you may leave and walk in the ways of peace.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jesus Ministers throughout the Land'
      title: Jesus Ministers throughout the Land
      number: 1
      content: "Soon afterward, Jesus began a ministry tour throughout the country,
        visiting cities and villages to announce the wonderful news [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of God\u2019s kingdom. His twelve disciples traveled with him "
      comments:
      - number: 8:1
        content: '  Jesus revealed fully what the law and the prophets did not fully
          reveal: the heart of the Father. This good news fulfills the ache of every
          human being to know a good Father who loves them.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'as did a number of women who had been healed of many illnesses and
        set free from demonic power. One of the women was Mary who was from the village
        of Magdala, [[COMMENT(0)]] from whom Jesus had cast out seven demons.  Among
        the women were Susanna and '
      comments:
      - number: 8:2
        content: "  Or \u201CMary Magdalene.\u201D The ancient village of Magdala
          has recently been discovered near the current town of Migdol. Some scholars
          believe Mary Magdalene could have been a rich widow since she financially
          supported the ministry of Jesus. In    she is named first among the women
          who cared for Jesus out of their own means.      The number seven means
          completeness. Mary was completely possessed by demons, but Jesus restored
          her true self and cast out her demons.    "
    - name: "3: Mysteries of God\u2019s Kingdom Realm"
      title: "Mysteries of God\u2019s Kingdom Realm"
      number: 3
      content: "Joanna, the wife of Chusa, who managed King Herod\u2019s household.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Many other women who supported Jesus\u2019 ministry from their
        own personal finances also traveled with him. "
      comments:
      - number: 8:3
        content: "  Some scholars believe that Chusa was the government official
          mentioned in  .      To travel with a rabbi was considered a high honor.
          Yet it was not permitted in the culture and time of Jesus\u2019 ministry
          for a woman to be mentored by a rabbi. Jesus elevated women into a place
          of honor and respect, in spite of the cultural limitations. It was these
          wealthy women who provided for Jesus\u2019 care. Luke is the one Gospel
          writer who brings out the many times Jesus honored women. These women would
          later be present at the crucifixion (;  ;  ,  ) and at the resurrection
          (). Mary Magdalene was the first human being to see the risen Christ ().    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Massive crowds gathered from many towns to hear Jesus, and he taught
        them using metaphors and parables, [[COMMENT(0)]] such as this:'
      comments:
      - number: 8:4
        content: "  One of Jesus\u2019 preferred teaching methods was through story
          (). A parable required the listener to be humble, teachable, and open to
          truth. Revelation from God can be found through the doorway of an allegory.
          This parable is described in the Aramaic as \u201Cthe parable of the seed.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CA farmer went out to sow seeds for a harvest. As he
        scattered his seeds, some of them fell on the hard pathway and were quickly
        trampled down and unable to grow and became nothing but bird seed.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "<JESUS>Some fell on the gravel, and though they sprouted they couldn\u2019t
        take root; it withered for lack of moisture.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: '<JESUS>Other seeds fell where there was nothing but weeds. They too
        were unable to grow to full maturity, for the weeds choked them out.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<JESUS>Yet some of the seeds fell into good, fertile soil, and they
        grew and flourished until they produced more than a hundredfold harvest,
        a bumper crop.\u201D</JESUS> Then Jesus added, shouting out to all who would
        hear, <JESUS>\u201CListen with your heart and you will understand!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Later his disciples came to him privately to ask him what deeper
        meaning they could find in this parable. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "He said, <JESUS>\u201CYou have been given a teachable heart to perceive
        the secret, hidden mysteries of God\u2019s kingdom realm. But to those without
        a listening heart, my words are merely stories. Even though they have eyes,
        they are blind to the true meaning of what I say,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>and even though they listen, they won\u2019t receive full revelation.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 8:10
        content: '  This is taken from  . See also  ;  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CHere, then, is the deeper meaning to my parable: The
        word of God</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>is the seed that is sown into
        hearts.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 8:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cmanifestation of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: '<JESUS>The hard pathway represents the hard hearts of those who hear
        the word of God but the slanderer</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>quickly
        snatches away what was sown in their hearts to keep them from believing and
        experiencing salvation.</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe devil.\u201D The Greek word    (also translated
          \u201Cdevil\u201D) means \u201Cthe slanderer.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: '<JESUS>The seeds falling on gravel represents those who initially
        respond to the word with joy, but soon afterward, when a season of difficulty
        and harassment of the enemy comes to them, they wither and fall away, for
        they have no root in the truth and their faith is temporary.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:13
        content: '  From the Aramaic text.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: '<JESUS>The seeds that fall into the weeds represents the hearts of
        those who hear the word of God but their growth is quickly choked off by
        their own anxious cares, the riches of this world, and the fleeting pleasures
        of this life. This is why they never become mature and fruitful.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: The Revelation Light'
      title: The Revelation Light
      number: 15
      content: "<JESUS>The seed that fell into good, fertile soil represents those
        lovers of truth who hear it deep within their hearts. They respond by clinging
        to the word, keeping it dear as they endure all things in faith. This is
        the seed that will one day bear much fruit in their lives.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CNo one lights a lamp and then hides it, covering it
        over or putting it where no one sees its light. No, he places the lamp on
        a lampstand so others benefit from its brightness.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "<JESUS>Because this revelation lamp now shines within you, nothing
        will be hidden from you\u2014it will all be revealed. Every secret</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>of the kingdom</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>will be unveiled and
        out in the open, made known by the revelation-light.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 8:17
        content: "  Implied in the context of Jesus\u2019 teaching on the mysteries
          of God\u2019s kingdom realm (v.  ).    "
    - name: "18: Jesus\u2019 True Family"
      title: "Jesus\u2019 True Family"
      number: 18
      content: "<JESUS>So pay careful attention to your hearts as you listen to my
        teaching, for to those who have open hearts, even more revelation will be
        given to them until it overflows. And for those who do not listen with open
        hearts, what little light they imagine themselves to have will be taken away.\u201D</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 8:18
        content: "  This verse contains a complicated ellipsis, which is a literary
          function of omitting certain information to invite discovery. The ellipsis
          of the text has been supplied by making explicit what is implicit in the
          context. The parables of the sower and of the lamp are similar, in that
          they speak of the heart that receives truth. The word of the kingdom is
          a \u201Cseed\u201D that grows within us and a \u201Clamp\u201D that glows
          within us.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Jesus\u2019 mother and his brothers [[COMMENT(0)]] came to where
        Jesus was teaching, but they couldn\u2019t get through the crowd that had
        gathered around him. "
      comments:
      - number: 8:19
        content: "  Mary had other sons and daughters. These were the half-brothers/sisters
          of Jesus. Jesus\u2019 father was not Joseph, but the Father of eternity.
          See also  .    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Someone told Jesus, \u201CYour mother and brothers [[COMMENT(0)]]
        are standing outside, wanting to speak with you.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 8:20
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '21: Peace in the Storm'
      title: Peace in the Storm
      number: 21
      content: "Jesus told the crowd, <JESUS>\u201CThese who come to listen to me
        are like my mother and my brothers. They\u2019re the ones who long to hear
        God\u2019s words and put them into practice.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '22-23: '
      title: 
      number: 22-23
      content: "One day Jesus said to his disciples, <JESUS>\u201CLet\u2019s get
        in a boat and go across to the other side of the lake.\u201D</JESUS> So they
        set sail, and soon Jesus fell asleep. But a fierce wind arose and became
        a violent squall that threatened to swamp their boat. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22-23: '
      title: 
      number: 22-23
      content: "One day Jesus said to his disciples, <JESUS>\u201CLet\u2019s get
        in a boat and go across to the other side of the lake.\u201D</JESUS> So they
        set sail, and soon Jesus fell asleep. But a fierce wind arose and became
        a violent squall that threatened to swamp their boat. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Alarmed, the disciples woke Jesus up and said, \u201CMaster, Master,
        we\u2019re sinking! Don\u2019t you care that we\u2019re going to drown?\u201DWith
        great authority Jesus rebuked the howling wind and surging waves, and instantly
        they became calm. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: A Demonized Man Set Free'
      title: A Demonized Man Set Free
      number: 25
      content: "Then Jesus said to them, <JESUS>\u201CWhy are you fearful? Have you
        lost your faith</JESUS>  <JESUS>in me</JESUS><JESUS>?\u201D</JESUS>Shocked,
        they said with amazement to one another, \u201CWho is this man [[COMMENT(0)]]
        who has authority over winds and waves that they obey him?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 8:25
        content: "  The answer to that question is found in  , \u201CHe is the Lord
          of hosts!\u201D    "
    - name: '26-29: '
      title: 
      number: 26-29
      content: "As soon as they stepped ashore on the eastern side of the lake in
        the land of the Gerasenes, the disciples were confronted by a demon-possessed
        madman from a nearby town. Many times he had been put under guard and bound
        with chains, but the many demons inside him had repeatedly thrown him into
        convulsions, breaking his shackles and driving him out of the town into the
        countryside. He had been demonized for a long time and was living naked in
        a cemetery among the tombs. When he saw Jesus, he fell at his feet and screamed
        out, \u201CWhat are you doing here? You are Jesus, the Son of the Most High
        God!\u201DJesus commanded the demons to come out of him, and they shouted,
        \u201CWe beg you, don\u2019t torture us!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26-29: '
      title: 
      number: 26-29
      content: "As soon as they stepped ashore on the eastern side of the lake in
